HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 7
BY REPRESENTATIVE BAYHAM
COMMENDATIONS: Commends the pivotal contributions made by Bernardo de Gálvez
and other Hispanic people during the American Revolution
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To commend the pivotal contributions made by Bernardo de Gálvez and other Hispanic
3 people to the success of the American Revolution.
4 WHEREAS, the United States achieved independence not only through the efforts
5 of American Revolutionaries but also because of the contributions and commitment of allied
6 foreign powers like Spain; Spain entered the war as a French ally in 1779 and provided
7 support to revolutionaries by means of funds and supplies and by land and sea military
8 operations; and
9 WHEREAS, the first foreign weapons for the Revolution came from Spain in early
10 1775 as a result of a petition from the Congress of Massachusetts; these supply lines were
11 achieved using the long-established commercial relations between coastal merchants and
12 Spanish traders such as Diego de Gardoqui from Bilbao; and
13 WHEREAS, Spain appointed Juan de Miralles as representative to the Continental
14 Congress of Philadelphia in 1779 and had several meetings about strategy and funding
15 matters with George Washington in his Sommerville and Morristown headquarters in New
16 Jersey; he passed away in May 1780 due to illness contracted during his mission; and
17 WHEREAS, Spain opened its ports to the Continental Navy ships and United States
18 privateers; Spain also sent a huge combat force of eleven thousand soldiers and twelve
19 thousand sailors aboard a hundred ships to Havana in 1780 to fight in America; and
